                        <h1>Home Networking</h1>                                  
                        Propelled by the proliferation of broadband and inexpensive PC networking gear, including Wi-Fi wireless gateways and routers, home networking has been one of the biggest success stories in the consumer technology arena in the past decade. <BR><BR>Now, experts say, the home networking market is entering a new phase in its evolution driven largely by Internet-connected CE products and related Web-based services. As you plan your time for the 2009 International CES, consider these trends: 
<UL>
<LI>The breadth of products connected to home networks will continue to increase, encompassing a greater variety of CE devices and a new generation of PC-connected digital media adapters and "extenders." </LI>
<LI>Service providers will play a major role in expanding the penetration of home networks and multimedia- or entertainment-oriented networking products centered on the delivery of Web-based content, primarily video. </LI>
<LI>Energy management concerns will continue to drive the installation of networked home automation systems. </LI>
<LI>Wireless technologies including ZigBee, Z-Wave, WiMAX and femtocells will proliferate as key home networking infrastructure technologies. </LI>
<LI>Though there will be important technological advances in home networking in 2008, many of these will be evolutionary, not revolutionary.</LI></UL><A href="/register">Register today for the 2009 International CES</A> to learn, network and investigate new technology&nbsp;in the&nbsp;home networking industry and many other consumer technology markets. It's free if you sign up before November 1. <BR><BR><EM><SPAN class=smallText>Source: Digital America, a CEA publication.</SPAN></EM>

